BIRDS.

Paraguay has scarcely any European bird, except the swallow, but it abounds in native ones, foreign to Europe. The former excel in the sweetness of their voice, the latter in the elegance of their plumage. Out of many Ι will describe a few.

THE HUMMlNG- BIRD.

The most curious is a bird, which is the smallest, and at the same time the most beauti- ful of all the winged tribe. The Spaniards have with justice named it picaflor, for it plucks the fiowers out of which it sucks juice like a bee. It charnis the eye with the exquisite beauty of its colour and plumage. The whole of its little body is scarce bigger than un olive or a nutmeg.
